<h2>Software</h2>

<b>Raid 5</b><br/>
Before i bought this machine a year ago, the question of soft/hard raid was haunting me. Wheter to use linux
mraid or anything else. Since i decided to use Windows as my primary OS, I decided to use the Onboard Raid
Controller which, as you can see above, is quite fast. One of the big issue with this method though, is that if
the motherboard gets fried, you will need to replace with the same model or else you will lose the Raid
array.<br/>
<br/>
<b>OS &amp; Apps</b><br/>
Decided to go with Windows because it's the OS i'm more confortable with. For the main interface, i use Steam Big
Picture and XBMC for easier navigation as both work with an X360 controller as the main input. I still use keyboard and
mouse for internet surfing and also to manage the computer and it's media files.<br/>
<br/>
Sickbeard is the main TV organizer. With it, I'm able to track every TV Show i want by the day. I use a custom
build provided by Bricky Box that you can find on his blog : <a href="http://brickybox.com/2013/05/09/sickbeard-with-integrated-torrent-client">brickybox.com/2013/05/09/sickbeard-with-integrated-torrent-client</a>.<br/>
<br/>
<b>Gaming</b>
<br/>
As you can see, there is no GPU card in this setup. With the new feature on Steam called In-Home streaming, The
lack of a GPU card doesn't really matter. I can easily stream games from my main office PC and i got almost no
lag while being at full settings. And while the APU isnt the best for gaming, it is comparable to a 7660D which
is quite able to play 2d games like Castle&nbsp;Crasher, Pixel Junk, Hearthstone or any emulator. Of course,
once the streaming won't be able to satisfied my needs, i will probably add a card for gaming.
